Wash and dry produce. Dice @potatoes{12%oz} into ½-inch pieces. Place in a small #pot{} with enough salted water to cover by 2 inches. Bring to a boil; cook until tender, ~{10-12%minutes}. Drain.

Halve, peel, and thinly slice @yellow onion{1}(peeled and thinly sliced). Core, deseed, and thinly slice @green bell pepper{1}(core removed and thinly sliced).

Place @cream cheese{2%tbsp} in a medium #microwave-safe bowl{}; cover. Microwave until softened, ~{25-30%seconds}. Whisk in @eggs{4}, @salt{3/4%tsp}, and @pepper{} to taste. Stir in half the @cheddar cheese{1/2%cup}(shredded).

Melt @butter{2%tbsp} in a medium, preferably nonstick, pan over medium-high heat. Add onion; season with salt and pepper. Cook, stirring, until lightly browned, ~{3-4%minutes}. Add bell pepper; cook, stirring, until softened, ~{2-3%minutes}. Turn off heat; transfer to a #plate{}. Wipe out pan.

Return pan to medium heat. Melt @butter{1%tbsp}, then stir in cooked potatoes, onion mixture, and @Southwest spice blend{2%tbsp}; season with salt. Stir in egg mixture; top with remaining cheddar. Cover pan with #lid{} or #foil{} and cook until frittata is set in the middle, ~{5-7%minutes}. Transfer to a plate.

> For 16 servings, use 4 TBSP butter for caramelizing, half the cooked potatoes, half the onion mixture, and half the Southwest Spice Blend. Also, use half the egg mixture and half the remaining cheddar. For larger batches, repeat to make second frittata.

== Hot Sauce Crema ==

When ready to serve, in a small #bowl{}, combine @sour cream{1.5%tbsp} and @hot sauce{1%tsp} to taste. Add @water{} 1 tsp at a time until mixture reaches a drizzling consistency; season with @salt{}. Dice @tomato{1}(diced); season with salt and pepper.

== To Serve ==

Carefully cut frittata into 8 wedges and reheat if necessary. Divide between #plates{}; top with crema and tomato. Serve.

> This vegetarian frittata is also a leftovers bonanza that tastes even better the next day!

> Wash hands and surfaces after handling raw eggs. Consuming raw or undercooked eggs may increase your risk of foodborne illness.